**B. BEFORE the existing `GET /reports` route (before line 83), insert POST `/reports` alias:**

This is the most critical ordering constraint: `/reports/generate` is static and is already registered first (line 75), so the compat POST `/reports` must come before `GET /reports` to avoid the `GET /reports` block shadowing the route segment, but since they use different HTTP verbs (POST vs GET), there is actually no conflict. The real concern is that `POST /reports` and `POST /reports/generate` could conflict if Express tries to match `/reports` as a prefix of `/reports/generate`. However since both are `POST` and Express matches exactly, `POST /reports/generate` registered first will match `/reports/generate` and `POST /reports` registered after will match `/reports` only. This ordering is safe as long as `/reports/generate` is registered before `/reports`.

```typescript
// COMPAT: frontend calls POST /reports instead of POST /reports/generate
router.post(
  '/reports',
  requireAuth,
  requireRole(...analyticsRoles),
  validate({ body: GenerateReportSchema }),
  controller.generateReport,
);
```

Place this immediately after the existing `POST /reports/generate` block (after line 81) and before `GET /reports` (line 83).

**C. After the existing `DELETE /reports/:id/share/:userId` block (after line 113), add share aliases:**
```typescript
// COMPAT: frontend calls POST /reports/:id/shares
router.post(
  '/reports/:id/shares',
  requireAuth,
  requireRole(...managerRoles),
  validate({ params: IdParamSchema, body: ShareReportSchema }),
  controller.shareReport,
);

// COMPAT: frontend calls DELETE /reports/:id/shares/:shareId (shareId = userId)
router.delete(
  '/reports/:id/shares/:shareId',
  requireAuth,
  requireRole(...managerRoles),
  validate({ params: z.object({ id: z.string().uuid(), shareId: z.string().uuid() }) }),
  (req, res, next) => {
    // Bridge: shareId in frontend maps to userId in canonical route
    req.params.userId = req.params.shareId;
    next();
  },
  controller.revokeShare,
);
```

Wait — `ReportShareParamSchema` validates `{ id, userId }`. The inline param validation above introduces a `z` import concern. Instead, the cleanest approach is to skip the validate middleware and let the controller read directly, since `revokeShare` only calls `req.params.id` and `req.params.userId`. The middleware pattern is:

```typescript
router.delete(
  '/reports/:id/shares/:shareId',
  requireAuth,
  requireRole(...managerRoles),
  (req: Request, _res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
    req.params.userId = req.params.shareId; // normalize for revokeShare controller
    next();
  },
  controller.revokeShare,
);
```

Add `NextFunction` to the express import at line 1, and `Request, Response` are already imported.

